=begin pod

=head1 NAME

B<Holidays::US::Federal> - Provides names, dates, and dates observed for US Federal holidays

=head1 SYNOPSIS

=begin code :lang<raku>

use Holidays::US::Federal;

=end code

=head1 DESCRIPTION

B<Holidays::US::Federal> is a module that provides information on
the eleven official U.S. federal holidays as of 2023-03-08 according to data
available online at 
L<https://www.opm.gov/policy-data-oversight/pay-leave/federal-holidays/>.
A description of the rules for traditional dates and when holidays are 
actually observed as paid holidays off for federal employees
is also found on the site. All the data reflect current laws
in 5 US Code 6103.

This module provides a routine which provides a hash of the holidays
for a given year keyed by each holiday's C<date>.
Each key is a Raku C<Date> and the key's value is 
a C<class FedHoliday> object.
The data are perpetual for any given 
year as long as 5 US Code 6103 stays unchanged.

For this collection there should be no overlapping holidays.
Each instance is one with two different date attributes:
(1) the traditional C<date> and (2) the C<date-observed>
which is the paid day-off for most federal government employees (as well as
for many other employees in the US labor force).
If the dates are identical, then that date is the one to use on a calendar.
If they are different, then both should be used.

Note the holidays also have a C<short-name> attribute which is not official
but has the value used by the author for his calendars.

=begin item 
NOTE: During the devlopment of this module, functions for finding dates relative
to other dates were found to be necessary and were coded and published
as a new Raku module: B<Date:Utils>. Those routines are expected to be
useful for various calendar creation. They are:

=item C<nth-day-of-week-in-month>
=item C<nth-day-of-week-after-date>

For convenience, the routines have alternative names requiring fewer
key strokes. They are:

=item C<nth-dow-in-month>
=item C<nth-dow-after-date>

=end item

